Generally, there are significant differences in forklength at release among years, with 2021 fish larger than the rest. Although significant, changes defined by fish condition at release are more subtle (see figures 2 & 3; ANOVA and post-hoc Tukey, not shown). Fish grew at an average AG of 10.90mm (sd 12.57923) and IGR of 2.279299×10−4 (sd 2.614755×10−4;Table S4), although among these 250 fish presented and average negative AG of 5.24mm and traveled an average of 1140 m and measured 155 mm at release (compared to 1418 fish with positive growth, with an average AG of 14.3 mm, average distance traveled of 644 m and average forklenght at release of 138mm). The minimum observed change in forklenght was detected for an individual fish that shrank 48mm (lowest IGR = -1.064) after 351 days released with group 6 (Deemer) in 2021 and recaptured at 2.757 km from where it was originally released. The maximum observed change in forklenght was 119 mm for an individual fish caught after 350 days released with group 4 (Gypsy Pools) in 2022 and recaptured at 157 meters from where it was originally released. The maximum IGR was 2.385806×10−3 for an individual fish released in 2019 (forklenght at release 88mm) with group 5 (X), and recaptured after 327 days having displaced 174 meters.
Two-way anova indicate a significant effect of release year and release group on both growth AG (p-values < 0.001; F = 84.8; F = 71.4) and IGR (p-values < 0.001; F = 95.0; F = 71.0). Post-hoc tukey test results indicate that release year 2021 was markedly lower from other years in both AG and IGR.  Fish group 5 (X) and 3 (Upper Sullivan) have significantly higher AG and IGR (results not shown but available upon request). Negative growth is more likely to be observed for fish that move more (t-test, p<0.001) as well as for those with larger sizes at release (t-test, p<0.001). 


## Possible themes for discussion
These analyses showed that larger size at release and higher-distances-moved are significantly related to slower or no growth in one-year after release in yy male EBT introduced in the Pend Oreille tributaries. Differences occur also depending on the year of release cohort possibly because of the fish size at release (Fig. 2) and group of release. 
What could the implications of these results mean? Fish grow at different rates throughout their life time. Introducing larger fish into the system may have allowed the ones that have already attained larger sizes before their introduction to allocate less effort to growth and to move more (Fig 4). 

